06002nam a22008175i 9780674275669DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742756697 a10.4159/97806742756692doi  a(DE-B1597)626849  a(OCoLC)1328135061  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aPN4784.S4 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a070.5092223/eng/202206231 aFitzpatrick, Shanon, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTrue Story :bHow a Pulp Empire Remade Mass Media /cShanon Fitzpatrick. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. Decades of Fitness in the Dynamic Midwest -- t2. The Transatlantic Birth of the Physical Culture Publishing Company -- t3. Circulating Physiques in an Age of Imperialism and Migration -- t4. Building Up the Nation during the First World War -- t5. The Sensational Rise of Macfadden Publications Inc. -- t6. The Great Depression and the Macfadden Market -- t7. International Issues, Foreign Editions, and the Global Popular -- t8. From the World of Tomorrow to the American Century -- tEpilogue : Pulp Empire Today -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe larger-than-life story of Bernarr Macfadden, a bodybuilder who turned his obsession with muscles, celebrity, and confession into a publishing empire that transformed global media. In True Story, Shanon Fitzpatrick tells the unlikely story of an orphan from the Ozarks who became one of history’s most powerful media moguls. Born in 1868 in Mill Spring, Missouri, Bernarr Macfadden turned to bodybuilding to transform himself from a sickly “boy” into a creature of masculine perfection. He then channeled his passion into the magazine Physical Culture, capitalizing on the wider turn-of-the-century mania for fitness. Macfadden Publications soon become a pioneer in mass media, helping to inaugurate our sensational, confessional, and body-obsessed global marketplace. With publications like True Story, a magazine purportedly written and edited by its own readers, as well as scores of romance, crime, and fan magazines, Macfadden specialized in titles that targeted women, immigrants, and the working class. Although derided as pulp by critics of the time, Macfadden’s publications were not merely profitable. They were also influential. They championed reader engagement and interactivity long before these were buzzwords in the media industry, breaking down barriers between producers and consumers of culture. At the same time, Macfadden Publications inspired key elements of modern media strategy by privileging rapid production of new content and equally rapid disintegration and reconfiguration of properties in the face of shifting market conditions. No less than the kings of Hollywood and Madison Avenue, Macfadden was a crucial player in shaping American consumer culture and selling it to the world at large. Though the Macfadden media empire is overlooked today, its legacies are everywhere, from true-crime journalism to celebrity gossip rags and fifteen-minute abs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHealth in mass mediaxHistoryy20th century. 0aMass mediazUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPhysical fitnesszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPulp literature, AmericanxHistoryy20th century. 0aSensationalism in journalismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aAmerican empire.  aPhysical Culture Publishing Company.  acultural empire.  acultural imperialism.  aglobalization.